ry, Devon, England"},"nl":{"about 1270–":"circa 1270–Overleden","1270–Male":"1270–Overleden","1274–Female":"1274–Overleden","1300–1332":"1300–1332","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","1251–Female":"1251–Overleden","about 1270":"circa 1270","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","ABT 1295":"circa 1295","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Throwleigh, Devon, England":"Throwleigh, Devon, England","(,, Devonshire, England)":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Musbury, Devon, England":"Musbury, Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1270–":"about 1270–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1274–Female":"1274–Deceased","1300–1332":"1300–1332","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1251–Female":"1251–Deceased","about 1270":"about 1270","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","ABT 1295":"about 1295","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Throwleigh, Devon, England":"Throwleigh, Devon, England","(,, Devonshire, England)":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Musbury, Devon, England":"Musbury, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hampton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Hampton, including the cities of Southampton and Northampton (both of which were originally simply <i>Hamtun</i>). These all share the final Old English element <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, but the first is variously <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’, <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow’, or <i>hēan</i>, weak dative case (originally used after a preposition and article) of <i>hēah</i> ‘high’. This surname is also found in Ireland, having first been taken there in the medieval period.","History: The descendants of the clergyman Thomas Hampton, resident at Jamestown, VA, in 1630, lived in VA through three generations, multiplying their homesteads as the colony expanded and then branched into SC. This very common English name was brought independently to North America by many other bearers."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Warren","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is of Norman origin, a coalescence of two different surnames, one derived from a Germanic personal name based on the element <i>war(in)</i> ‘guard’ and the other from a place in Normandy called <i>La Varenne</i> ‘the game park’. The Norman personal name survived at least into the 17th century in Yorkshire, where it was particularly associated with the Scargill family. In America this name has sometimes been chosen in honour of  General Joseph Warren , the first hero of the American Revolution, who was killed at  Bunker Hill  (  1775 ). Among modern influences on the choice of the name has been the film actor  Warren Beatty  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":67,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":112,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Warren Hampton was born about 1270, his father, Norton Hampton, was 21 and his mother, Mrs. Norton Hampton, was 20. He married Phillipa D'Orway about 1295, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Musbury, Devon, England."},"et":{"about 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1300–1332":"1300–1332","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1251–Female":"1251–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","ABT 1295":"umbes 1295","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Throwleigh, Devon, England":"Throwleigh, Devon, England","(,, Devonshire, England)":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Musbury, Devon, England":"Musbury, Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1274–Female":"1274–Kuollut","1300–1332":"1300–1332","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1251–Female":"1251–Kuollut","about 1270":"noin 1270","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"131